<section class="card">
  <h2>About Potatoes</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes (Solanum tuberosum) are cool-season crops grown for underground tubers.
    They handle cool weather well, and are often planted <strong>before</strong> the average last spring frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, potatoes are a practical staple crop because they grow reliably in cool conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Tolerance & Temperature Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Best growth:</strong> 60–70°F (16–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> sustained highs above ~85°F (29°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Light frost:</strong> foliage can be damaged around 30–32°F (-1 to 0°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Soil buffer:</strong> tubers are protected by soil and mulch/hilling</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Frost can damage leaves, but plants often recover if growing points are protected.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planting Window</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes are typically planted in early spring once soil can be worked.
    In many regions, this is 2–4 weeks before the average last frost.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Plant seed potatoes in cool, workable soil (not waterlogged).</li>
    <li>Expect slower emergence in cold soil—this is normal.</li>
    <li>Hill soil up around stems as plants grow to protect developing tubers.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Soil & Site Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Full sun is ideal, but potatoes tolerate slightly less than fruiting crops.</li>
    <li>Loose, well-drained soil reduces misshapen tubers.</li>
    <li>Hilling (or deep mulch) keeps tubers covered and prevents greening.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Avoid compacted, saturated soil—potatoes need oxygen at the root zone.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Variety Considerations</h2>

  <p>
    Choose varieties based on your season length and harvest goals.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Early potatoes:</strong> quicker harvest and good for short seasons.</li>
    <li><strong>Maincrop potatoes:</strong> larger yield but require a longer season.</li>
    <li><strong>Storage types:</strong> often maincrop varieties with longer maturity.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Early varieties reduce frost risk on the back end of the season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Fall Frost Considerations</h2>

  <p>
    Potatoes can be harvested after the first light frosts,
    but hard freezes can damage exposed tubers.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>If foliage is killed by frost, tubers can still be harvested soon after.</li>
    <li>Before a hard freeze, ensure tubers are well covered with soil or mulch.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If growing for storage, harvest on a dry day and allow skins to set before long-term storage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I plant potatoes before the last frost?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes. Potatoes are commonly planted weeks before the last frost as long as soil is workable.
      Late frosts may damage foliage, but plants often recover—especially if hilled.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>What if a frost hits after potato plants emerge?</summary>
    <p>
      Light frost may burn leaves. Cover plants temporarily, and keep soil hilled up.
      Many plants regrow from protected growing points.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Why hill potatoes?</summary>
    <p>
      Hilling protects tubers from light (prevents greening), reduces tuber exposure during cold snaps,
      and can improve yield by supporting tuber development.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Potatoes are cool-season crops and can be planted before the last frost.</li>
    <li>Foliage can be damaged by frost, but soil protects tubers.</li>
    <li>Hill plants to protect tubers and reduce greening.</li>
    <li>Choose early varieties to reduce end-of-season frost risk.</li>
  </ol>
</section>
